President Uhuru Kenyatta was Wednesday morning formally received in India by President Pranab Mukherjee and Prime Minister Narendra Modi at the official residence of the Indian President in New Delhi.The president was accorded an elaborate State reception complete with a 21-gun salute.President Uhuru Kenyatta inspects a guard of honor at the official residence of the Indian President in New Delhi. Photo/PSCU President Uhuru, who is on a reciprocal State visit to India, was escorted into the official residence of the Indian President by mounted troops shortly after 10:00 am (Indian time). The firing of 21 cannons at the ceremony traditionally reserved for Heads of State and Government was followed by the national anthems of Kenya and India played by the Indian military band.President Uhuru Kenyatta at the official residence of the Indian President in New Delhi. Photo/PSCUUhuru later inspected a guard of honour mounted by a detachment of the Indian military. Addressing the press after the ceremonies, President Uhuru said the reciprocal visit would further strengthen the cordial relations between Kenya and India. He said the visit would also boost the economic, cultural and social ties that the two countries have always enjoyed.President Uhuru Kenyatta at the official residence of the Indian President in New Delhi. Photo/PSCULater, the Head of State visited Raj Ghat (the Mahatma Gandhi Memorial) where he laid a wreath in remembrance of the legendary leader of the Indian independence struggle who inspired movements for civil rights and freedom across the world.